Part I - Superstore Dataset Exploration¶

by Goodrich Okoro¶

Introduction¶

Dataset containing Sales & Profit of a Superstore. This dataset can be found on Kaggle

For this project I will explore the dataset to understand which products, regions, categories and customer segments generate the highest and least sales, same for profit.

Metadata

Row ID => Unique ID for each row.
Order ID => Unique Order ID for each Customer.
Order Date => Order Date of the product.
Ship Date => Shipping Date of the Product.
Ship Mode=> Shipping Mode specified by the Customer.
Customer ID => Unique ID to identify each Customer.
Customer Name => Name of the Customer.
Segment => The segment where the Customer belongs.
Country => Country of residence of the Customer.
City => City of residence of the Customer.
State => State of residence of the Customer.
Postal Code => Postal Code of every Customer.
Region => Region where the Customer belongs.
Product ID => Unique ID of the Product.
Category => Category of the product ordered.
Sub-Category => Sub-Category of the product ordered.
Product Name => Name of the Product
Sales => Sales of the Product.
Quantity => Quantity of the Product.
Discount => Discount provided.
Profit => Profit/Loss incurred.

Code¶

In [ ]:
# changing "order_date" and "ship_date" to datetime data type
date_col = ['order_date', 'ship_date']
store_clean[date_col] = store_clean[date_col].apply(pd.to_datetime)

# changing "ship_mode" to ordered categorical data type
ship_order = ['Same Day', 'First Class', 'Second Class', 'Standard Class']
store_clean['ship_mode'] = pd.Categorical(store_clean['ship_mode'], 
                                                           ordered = True, categories = ship_order)

# changing "segment", "region", "category" and "sub_category" to category data type
cat_col = ['segment', 'region', 'category', 'sub_category']
store_clean[cat_col] = store_clean[cat_col].astype('category')

# changing "postal_code" to string data type
store_clean['postal_code'] = store_clean['postal_code'].astype(str)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset contains 9,994 entries of product sold with 20 fields that give details about the product such as; ship date, ship mode, region, product name, sales, quantity, profit, e.t.c.,There a five (5) categorical fields, ship mode being one of it is a ordered categorical type. Only four fields are numeric in nature, sales, quantity,discount, and profit.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in knowing which category is making the most sales, and if the category with the most sales is actually generating the highest profit. In the process, I'll get to know which states contribute most to this.

I'm also interested in knowing the average sales and profit made from each category, region and segment.

There is a loss (negative profit) in the dataset. I'm interested in knowing which states have loss, then investigate for more details and find out how the category contributes to the loss.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Sales and profit will play a major role in my investigation, then these categories ship mode, segment, region, and category, will help narrow down the investigation for more details.

Category Count

Here we would see the most ordered category as well as sub-category.

In [ ]:
# Creating a function to create a countplot into a subplot for a given category variable.

color = sb.color_palette("Paired")[1]
def cat_count_plot(cat):
    if cat == 'ship_mode':
        sb.countplot(data = store_sub, x = cat, color = color )
        plt.xlabel('{}'.format(cat.replace("_"," ")));
    elif cat == 'sub_category':
        freq = store_sub[cat].value_counts()
        order = freq.index
        sb.countplot(data = store_sub, y = cat, color = color, order = order)
        plt.ylabel('{}'.format(cat.replace("_"," ")));
    else:
        freq = store_sub[cat].value_counts()
        order = freq.index
        sb.countplot(data = store_sub, x = cat, color = color, order = order)
        plt.xlabel('{}'.format(cat.replace("_"," ")));
In [ ]:
# Iterating through a list of categorical variable for plotting.

cat_lst = ['ship_mode', 'segment', 'region', 'category', 'sub_category']
for cat_name in cat_lst:
    fig = plt.figure()
    fig.set_figwidth(18)
    fig.set_figheight(18)
    plt.subplot(3,2,1)
    cat_count_plot(cat_name)

Here's a brief note on ship mode. Ship mode: This field contains four unique values that depicts the duration it will take for the consumer to receive the product. Same Day: Shipping on Same Day First Class: Shipping within 1 Day Second Class: Shipping within 3 Days Standard Class: Shipping within 6 Days

From the plot, standard class is the most commonly used ship mode, this may be as a result of the majority customers being far from shop location, or cost of standard class. Home office is the least segment in the data.

Generally,the West has the highest count of products sold.

Interesting! Products in the Office Supply category are the most sold products. Furniture and Technology product bought is not up to half of product sold in the Office Supplies. In the sub category, Blinders has the highest count while Copiers has the least count.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The sales field when plotted on a standard histogram had a right skewed distribution, it also has a long tail of distribution so I used log transformation to plot the sales variable again. This time the data looked unimodal with the highest peak between \$10 and $100.

The profit distribution looks like a uniform distribution, it also has a negative value with a long tail on both sides (negative and positive). Profit also has a long tail distribution so I used log transformation on the positive part of the profit (We can not perform log on negative values), and it has a unimodal shape with the highest peak below 20 dollars.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?s¶

While investigating, I had to know how the product being ordered changed across the year so I generated a year column which changed the form of the data.

# A function to create a scatter plot for two numeric variable with conditions base on current data
def relationship(num_var1,num_var2):
    sb.regplot(data = store_sub, x= num_var1, y = num_var2, x_jitter = 0.05,
        scatter_kws = {'alpha':0.3, 's':30}, fit_reg = False)
    plt.title('{}'.format(num_var1 + ' vs ' + num_var2))
    if num_var1 == 'profit':
        plt.xlabel('{} ($)'.format(num_var1))
    elif num_var1 == 'sales':
        plt.xlabel('{} ($)'.format(num_var1))
    else:
        plt.xlabel('{}'.format(num_var1))
        
    if num_var2 == 'profit':
        plt.ylabel('{} ($)'.format(num_var2))
    elif num_var2 == 'sales':
        plt.ylabel('{} ($)'.format(num_var2))
    else:
        plt.ylabel('{}'.format(num_var2))
In [ ]:
# A function to create a scatter plot for two numeric variable with conditions base on current data
def log_relationship(num_var1,num_var2):
    sb.regplot(data = store_sub, x= num_var1, y = num_var2, x_jitter = 0.05,
        scatter_kws = {'alpha':0.3, 's':30}, fit_reg = False)
    plt.title('{}'.format(num_var1 + ' vs ' + num_var2))
    plt.yscale('symlog')
    plt.yticks([-1000, -100, -10, -1, 0, 1, 10, 100, 1000],
              ['-1k', '-100', '-10', '-1', '0', '1', '10', '100', '1000']);
    if num_var1 == 'profit':
        plt.xscale('symlog')
        plt.xticks([-1000, -100, -10, -1, 0, 1, 10, 100, 1000],
              ['-1k', '-100', '-10', '-1', '0', '1', '10', '100', '1000'])
        plt.xlabel('{} ($)'.format(num_var1))
    elif num_var1 == 'sales':
        plt.xscale('log')
        plt.xticks([1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000],['1', '10', '100', '1k', '10k'])
        plt.xlabel('{} ($)'.format(num_var1))
    else:
        plt.xlabel('{}'.format(num_var1))
        
    if num_var2 == 'profit':
        plt.yscale('symlog')
        plt.yticks([-1000, -100, -10, -1, 0, 1, 10, 100, 1000],
              ['-1k', '-100', '-10', '-1', '0', '1', '10', '100', '1000'])
        plt.ylabel('{} ($)'.format(num_var2))
    elif num_var2 == 'sales':
        plt.yscale('symlog')
        plt.yticks([-1000, -100, -10, -1, 0, 1, 10, 100, 1000],
              ['-1k', '-100', '-10', '-1', '0', '1', '10', '100', '1000'])
        plt.ylabel('{} ($)'.format(num_var2))
    else:
        plt.ylabel('{}'.format(num_var2))

In [ ]:
def count_category(cat1, cat2):
    reg_cat = store_sub.groupby([cat1, cat2]).size()
    reg_cat = reg_cat.reset_index(name = 'count')
    reg_cat = reg_cat.pivot(index = cat1, columns = cat2, 
                           values = 'count')
    sb.heatmap(reg_cat, annot = True, fmt = 'd', cmap = 'viridis_r',
              cbar_kws={'label': 'count'})
    plt.title('Count of each {} in each {}'.format(cat2, cat1));
In [ ]:
count_category('region','category')

interesting! It looks like office supplies are the big deal here because its column alone has the highest for all regions. Generally, west happens to have the highest count of category, i.e. 1,897 is the highest count of category (Office Supplies) sold to one region, and that region is West.

We saw already in the univariate section that West is the region with the most ordered products, and the heatmap above did not just confirm that but shows how product categories contribute to this.

# Scatter plot function to create a relation ship with shape encoding.
def prft_sales_encoding(var,mark):
    lst = []
    for cat, marker in mark:
        store_cat = store_sub[store_sub[var] == cat]
        plt.scatter(data = store_cat, x = 'sales', y = 'profit', 
                    marker = marker, s = 25, alpha = 0.4)
        plt.xlabel('sales ($)')
        plt.ylabel('profit ($)')
        plt.xscale('log')
        plt.yscale('symlog')
        plt.xticks([1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000],['1', '10', '100', '1k', '10k'])
        plt.yticks([-1000, -100, -10, -1, 0, 1, 10, 100, 1000],
                  ['-1k', '-100', '-10', '-1', '0', '1', '10', '100', '1000']);
        lst.append(cat)
    plt.legend(lst);

def barplot(cat_var1, num_var, cat_var2):

             hue =cat_var2, errwidth = 0)
    plt.ylabel('avg. {} ($)'.format(num_var));
In [ ]:
# Creating a function to plot a heatmap of two categorical with average value of numeric variable displayed
# Note this function takes the data to plot from as an input.
def avg_num_cats(cat1, num, cat2, data):
    reg_cat = data.groupby([cat1, cat2])[num].mean()
    reg_cat = reg_cat.reset_index(name = '{}'.format(num))
    reg_cat = reg_cat.pivot(index = cat1, columns = cat2, 
                           values = '{}'.format(num))
    sb.heatmap(reg_cat, annot = True, fmt = '.2f', cmap = 'viridis_r',
              cbar_kws={'label': 'avg. {} ($)'.format(num)})
    plt.title('Avg. {} of each {} in all {}'.format(num, cat2, cat1))
    plt.yticks(rotation=0);

# Heatmap plot function to display total of numeric variable across two categorical variable
def SubCatDetails(num_var):
    sub_cat = store_sub.groupby(['category', 'sub_category'])[num_var].sum()
    sub_cat = sub_cat.reset_index(name = 'total_{}'.format(num_var))
    name = 'total_{}'.format(num_var)
    sub_cat = sub_cat.query('{} != 0'.format(name))
    sub_cat = sub_cat.pivot(index = 'sub_category', columns = 'category', 
                           values = name )
    sb.heatmap(sub_cat, cmap = 'viridis_r', annot = True, fmt = '.2f',
              cbar_kws={'label': 'Total {} ($)'.format(num_var)})
    plt.title('Total {} in each sub-category'.format(num_var));
